<p><b>How to write Guru Nanak Dev ji in Punjabi?</b> Guru Nanak Dev Ji (Gurmukhi: ਗੁਰੂ ਨਾਨਕ), the founder and first Guru of Sikhism, was born in the year 1469, in the village Talwandi which is located in the Punjab region of the Indian subcontinent.</p>
<p><b>What is the famous writing of Guru Nanak Dev ji?</b> Guru Nanak's most important work is the Mool Mantar. The Mool Mantar was written after Guru Nanak's experience visiting God for three days and receiving enlightenment. The Mool Mantar can be found at the beginning of the holy Sikh scriptures, called the Guru Granth Sahib.</p>
<p><b>Who is Guru Nanak biography?</b> Guru Nanak (born April 15, 1469, Rai Bhoi di Talvandi [now Nankana Sahib, Pakistan], near Lahore, India—died 1539, Kartarpur, Punjab) was an Indian spiritual teacher who was the first Guru of Sikhism, a monotheistic religion that combines Hindu and Muslim influences.</p>
<p><b>What is Guru Nanak to Sikhs?</b> Guru Nanak is considered the first Sikh Guru. Sikhism is still based on his teachings and those of the nine Sikh Gurus who followed him.</p>
<p><b>Did Guru Nanak speak Punjabi?</b> Guru Nanak Dev Ji's Sayings are not in Punjabi per se. The Languages used in Guru Granth Sahib are collectively called 'Sant Bhasha' or 'Sadhu Bhasha'.</p>
<p><b>Was Guru Nanak born Hindu?</b> Guru Nanak's Life Embodied the Values He Taught. Born into a Hindu family of a high caste, Guru Nanak had a revelatory experience at a young age, denounced his faith and caste, and realized that “there is one God and one human race.”</p>
<p><b>Which gurbani is written by Guru Nanak Dev Ji?</b> The writings of Guru Nanak Dev ji were integrated into the scripture of Guru Granth Sahib by the fifth Guru Arjan Dev ji in the form of 974 spiritual hymns comprising the Japji Sahib, Asa di Var, Bara Mah, Sidh Gosht and Dakhni Onkar.</p>
<p><b>Who is the God of Sikhism?</b> Sikhs believe there is only one God, which is genderless and eternal. They refer to God as Waheguru. Sikhs believe in rebirth and karma, meaning their religion is a way of life and that in every action, they should remember God.</p>
<p><b>Did Guru Nanak have a wife?</b> Guru Nanak Ji was married to Bibi Sulakhani of Gurdaspur district at the age of fourteen. They had two sons named Sri Chand and Lakhmi Chand.</p>
<p><b>Who is God according to Guru Nanak Dev Ji?</b> Guru Nanak emphasized the “formless” God, spoken of as Nirankar. God may be spoken of in many ways—as Allah or Brahman, Ram or Rahim. But the great name of God is Truth. God cannot be known in any image or form; the Nirankar is invisible, infinite, beyond the confines of form.</p>
<p><b>What are the two main teachings of Guru Nanak?</b> The most famous teachings attributed to Guru Nanak are that there is only one God, and that all human beings can have direct access to God with no need of rituals or priests. His most radical social teachings denounced the caste system and taught that everyone is equal, regardless of caste or gender.</p>
